This table is NOT tidy. It has the same value for multiple rows for the same column. Instead, we can make cases and population column headers.

spread(table2, key = type, value = count)

  1. If we want to add a new column, we use the mutate() function. We need to use division to get the price per carat. We would mutate the old table and assign it to itself, overriding the old variable. This is what the code should look like.

diamonds <- mutate(diamonds, price_per_carat = price / carat)

diamonds %>% mutate(max = price > 10000, min = carat < 1.5) %>% group_by(cut) %>% summarise(count = n(), num = sum(max & min), prop = (num / count) * 100) 
## # A tibble: 5 x 4
##   cut       count   num  prop
##   <ord>     <int> <int> <dbl>
## 1 Fair       1610     4 0.248
## 2 Good       4906    17 0.347
## 3 Very Good 12082   155 1.28 
## 4 Premium   13791   173 1.25 
## 5 Ideal     21551   485 2.25

This tibble makes sense because of correlation. As the price increases, the carat size also increases. It is a little odd that even fair diamonds are priced so high. It seems like some are even priced the same as higher quality diamonds. It would be interesting to see why they are prices so highly.

  1. We can assume that there is a positive correlation between sales and listings. The more listings there are, the more houses there are to sell, meaning more sales. From the graph below we can see its a diminishing line. It does have a positive correlation as the line that we get from geom_smooth() has a positive slope, until the very end where it levels out and starts dipping towards the end.
ggplot(data = txhousing, mapping = aes(x = sales, y = listings)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth()
